fr:tree.fr:mainmatter:

We first unravel the first few M_k’s to get a better understanding.


  \begin {aligned}
   M_1 &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M_0\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n\oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  I^n\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  M
   \\
   M_2 &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M_1\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  {\mathopen {}\left (I^n \oplus  M\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  I^n\right )\mathclose {}} \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  M \oplus  M^2
  \end {aligned}



By induction, we can extend the pattern above to a closed form for each M_k. In particular, we deduce that M_k = \bigoplus _{l\leq  k} M^l by recalling from Lemma  that the identity matrix is the neutral element for matrix multiplication. Therefore, we have M_n =\bigoplus _{k \leq  n}M^k.


Our goal is to show that M_n = \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}} R^{\circ  *}; we have already seen in Lemma  and Lemma  that matrix addition corresponds to union of relations and matrix multiplication corresponds to relational composition.


By Observation  (Reflexive-transitive closure of finite endo-relations), we have R^{\circ *} = \bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}. Therefore:


  \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ *} = \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}\bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}



By Lemma  (matrix addition and union of relations), we have:


  \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}\bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}
  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ  k}


 By Lemma  (matrix product is relational composition), we have:

  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ  k}  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} {\mathopen {}\left (\operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R\right )\mathclose {}}^k
  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} M^k
  = M_n


We first unravel the first few M_k’s to get a better understanding.


  \begin {aligned}
   M_1 &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M_0\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n\oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  I^n\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  M
   \\
   M_2 &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M_1\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  {\mathopen {}\left (I^n \oplus  M\right )\mathclose {}}\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  I^n\right )\mathclose {}} \oplus  {\mathopen {}\left (M\otimes  M\right )\mathclose {}}
   \\
   &= I^n \oplus  M \oplus  M^2
  \end {aligned}



By induction, we can extend the pattern above to a closed form for each M_k. In particular, we deduce that M_k = \bigoplus _{l\leq  k} M^l by recalling from Lemma  that the identity matrix is the neutral element for matrix multiplication. Therefore, we have M_n =\bigoplus _{k \leq  n}M^k.


Our goal is to show that M_n = \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}} R^{\circ  *}; we have already seen in Lemma  and Lemma  that matrix addition corresponds to union of relations and matrix multiplication corresponds to relational composition.


By Observation  (Reflexive-transitive closure of finite endo-relations), we have R^{\circ *} = \bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}. Therefore:


  \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ *} = \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}\bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}



By Lemma  (matrix addition and union of relations), we have:


  \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}\bigcup _{k\leq  n} R^{\circ  k}
  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ  k}


 By Lemma  (matrix product is relational composition), we have:

  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} \operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R^{\circ  k}  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} {\mathopen {}\left (\operatorname {\underline {mat}}_{\mathbb {B}}R\right )\mathclose {}}^k
  =
  \bigoplus _{k\leq  n} M^k
  = M_n

